WHILE STRIPPING TRLR LO9521 FROM GREENSBORO. WE FOUND 1 SKID AT ADHESIVE PAINT WHILE CONTAINED 6 CTNS.  1 CTN HAD BEEN LEAKING AT SOME POINT, AND WAS WET NO PRODUCT LEAKED ON TRLR FLOOR, SO IT APPEARS TO HAVE HAPPENED BEFORE IT WAS LOADED, OR THAT IT LEAKED BRIEFLY AND THE ADHESIVE EVENTUALLY SEALED ITSELF. AFTER OPENING CARTONS WE FOUND NO DAMAGE TO THE PAILS. IT APPEARS THE PAILS WERE OLD AND RUSTED.

column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DEC 02 CAPTAIN OF CONTAINER VESSEL ESSEN EXPRESS ENROUTE FROM SEATTLE TO OAKLAND REPORTS STRONG ODOR ORIGINATING FROM SHIPMENT OF 4 TANK CONTAINERS LOADED IN CARGO HOLD BAY 21/23.  DEC 03 VESSEL ARRIVES AT OAKLAND ANCHORAGE ON CO-ORDINATION WITH USCG, OOCL (CARGO OPERATOR) AND YTI (TERMINAL OPERATOR).  HAZMAT TEAM DETECTS LEAKAGE IN CARGO HOLD AND STARTS DECONTAMINATION AND NEUTRALIZATION OF LEAKING TANK AND PRODUCT WITH DEGREASER.  OBTAINED PERMISSION FROM USCG TO DOCK AT BERTH 58.  VESSEL DOCKS AT 1520.  DISCHARGING CONTAINERS FROM DECK AT BAY 21/23.  OPENING HATCH COVER FOR VENTILATION.  RESUME DISCHARGE OPERATION AT 19.00. DISCHARGING ALL CONTAINERS FROM BAY 21/23 IN THE SPILL AREA INCLUDING HAZMAT TANK CONTAINERS IN ORDER TO CLEAN AND DECONTAMINATE THE CARGO HOLD. DEC 04 HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM (NCR ENVIRONMENT) CLEANS SPILL AREA IN BAY 21/23.  HAZMAT TEAM WILL TRANSFER BENZALDEHYDE FROM LEAKING TANK CONTAINER IN OTHER TANK CONTAINER.  ESSEN EXPRESS SAILS AFTER COMPLETION OF CARGO OPERATION AT 1418.  ON DECEMBER 05 IT WAS STILL IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE LEAKAGE FROM THE DEFECTIVE TANK BECAUSE OF THE INSULATION (CASING) AROUND THE TANK.

column168: TWO 12,000 GAL AGST IN BASEMENT.  TWO FILLS IN SIDEWALK W/VENT PIPE & OVERFILL AUDIBLE ALARM.  BLDG. ENGINEER DIRECTED DRIVER TO FILL.  WHILE OIL WAS BEING DELIVERED, MAINT. PERSON CAME OUT & SAID OIL WAS COMING OUT OF TOP OF TANK.  THE TANK WAS ALREADY FULL.  SPILL CONTAINED & CLEANED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THIS ENTIRE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 300 20 LITRE 3H1 PLASTIC JERRYCANS.  THEY WERE STACKED 3 HIGH ON SIDE OF CARGO AIRCRAFT PALLET, WHEN ONE OF OUR AGENTS BUMPED THE CARGO, CAUSING ONE OF THE JERRYCANS TO FALL OVER, AND STRIKE THE FLOOR.  THE HEIGHT WAS APPROXIMATELY 36 INCHES OFF OF THE GROUND.  THIS IMPACT CAUSED A SMALL FRACTURE IN THE TOP OF THE JERRYCAN, AND APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF LIQUID SPILLED OUT.  THE DUTY SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY INFORMED THE DEPARTMENT MANAGER.  WE THEN- 1.  RETRIEVED THE WAREHOUSE SPILL KIT.  WITH GLOVES ON, WE USED THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE SPILL KIT TO MOP UP THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE THAT SPILLED OUT OF THE TOP OF THE JERRYCAN.  WE THEN PLACED THE ENTIRE JERRYCAN, THE GLOVES, THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE PLASTIC LINER INTO THE YELLOW SPILL-KIT BARREL. 2.  WE NOTICED ALL REQUIRED AGENCIES IN THE FOLLOWING ORDER:  A.  LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT (310) 646-5000  B.  LOS ANGELES POLICE DEPARTMENT (310) 646-6615  C.  LOS ANGELES AIRPORT OPERATIONS OFFICE (310) 646-6615 D.  F.A.A. OFFICE FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (310) 725-3984.  THE AGENT WHO LOADED THESE CONTAINERS WAS CAUTIONED TO USE GREATER CARE WHEN LOADING DANGEROUS GOODS OF THIS TYPE, ESPECIALLY IF THEY ARE TO BE STACKED ON TOP OF EACH OTHER.

WEAVERTOWN DISCOVERED 4 DRUMS WITHOUT A GASKET ON THE BUNG.  1 DRUM WITH A LOOSE BUNG AND 1 DRUM THAT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED.  WEAVERTOWN REPLACED THE 4 DEFECTIVE BUNGS AND OVERPAKED THE 2 DRUMS.  ALL MATERIAL WAS DELIVERED TO DESTINATION ALONG WITH THE REST OF THE LOAD.

BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN (1/3 OPENED) WITH THE CORRESPONDING 3 INCH PLUG UNSECURED & LAYING ATOP THIS VALVE.  RESPONDER CLOSED VALVE, APPLIED & TOOL TIGHTENED PLUG ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE.  SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED.

I/C EMPLOYEE WAS PLACING A BOX AND 6 GALLON BUCKET ONTO CONVEYOR. THE BUCKET SPLIT OPEN DOWN AT THE BASS OF THE CONTAINER, SPILLING OUT APPROXIMATELY 1-2 LITERS OF LIQUID CONTENTS.  I WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY. I CLEARED THE HAZMAT OUT OF THE WAREHOUSE, PULLED OUT THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE AND CONTACTED THE HAZ-HOTLINE.  REVIEWED THE SITUATION WITH MAT ? DEPT AND HE INFORMED ME TO EVACUATE FACILITY AND CONTACT LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  MATT CONTACTED THE HAZ SPILL TEAM.  UPDATED MATT AND MY DISTRICT MANAGER THROUGHOUT THE EVENT.  WE WERE CLEARED BY THE HAZ SPILL TEAM TO RE-ENTER THE FACILITY AT 1140.

column168: A DRIVER FOR AAA PROPANE HAD JUST RETURNED TO HIS STORAGE LOCATION AT 5641 DAVIDSON RD., PLACERVILLE, CALIFORNIA WHEN HE HEARD A "POP" AND DISCOVERED LIQUID PROPANE LEAKING FROM A PUMP SEAL.  THE TANK INTERNAL VALVE WAS CLOSED BUT WHEN THE LEAK DID NOT SLOW OR STOP AFTER A FEW MINUTES, EMPLOYEES AT AAA PROPANE REALIZED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS MALFUNCTIONING.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO DISBURSE THE LIQUID PROPANE WHILE THE PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED INTO ANOTHER TRUCK TANK.  THE REMAINING VAPOR WAS THEN SAFELY FLARED IN ORDER TO TOTALLY ELIMINATE THE LEAK AND THE INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED.  NO INJURIES WERE SUFFERED, NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE AND NO MAJOR ROADS WERE CLOSED DUE TO THE RELEASE. PRODUCT LOST IS ESTIMATED AT 112 GALLONS.

DURING THE AM DELIVERY CYCLE, THE COURIER NOTICED A STRONG "SOLVENT" SMELL IN HER TRUCK.  SHE PULLED OVER AND CALLED DISPATCH TO REPORT THE LEAK AND ODOR IN HER VEHICLE.  A SPILL CLEAN UP SPECIALIST WAS SENT TO HER VEHICLE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND CLEAN UP OTHER FREIGHT WHICH HAD BECOME CONTAMINATED.  THE MSDS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER SHOWED THE FLASH POINT OF THE MATERIAL AS BLANK (OR COVERED WITH WHITE-OUT).  HOWEVER, UNDER THE SECTION RELATED TO FIRE WARNINGS LABELING, THE WORDS "EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE" WERE THERE.  IN OUR OPINION, THIS SHIPMENT WAS OF A FLAMMABLE NATURE AND WAS SHIPPED AS AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE CHICAGO FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: AT 5:45 PM ON DECEMBER 3, 2003 A TRUCK TRANSPORTATION INCIDENT OCCURRED INVOLVING A SHIPMENT OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL ( MANIFEST ATTACHMENT 1) FROM NASA - PLUM BROOK REACTOR DECOMMISSIONING SITE IN SANDUSKY, OHIO TO THE INTERMODAL TRANSFER FACILITY IN  CONWAY, PENNSYLVANIA. A BULK SHIPMENT OF RADIOACTIVE CONSTRUCTION DEBRIS [ FOUR LARGE METAL PIECES ] CONTAINED WITHIN A 25.4 CUBIC YARD IP-1 INTERMODAL CONTAINER, THE CONTAINER WAS BREACHED IN THE INCIDENT. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN A DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC. DRIVER [ A VENDOR TO MHF-LS ] STOP SUDDENLY TO AVOID A POTENTIAL ACCIDENT WITH AN AUTOMOBILE CAUSING THE LOAD INSIDE THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER TO SHIFT FORWARD CAUSING THE LOADTHE LOAD TO BEACH THE CONTAINER (PICTURES ATTACHMENT 2 ). THE DRIVER NOTED THAT THERE WAS A LARGE "THUD" BUT CONTINUED ON TO THE FINAL DESTINATION WHICH HE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE AWAY FROM ARRIVING. THERE WERE NO PROPERTY DAMAGE, INJURIES, OR CONTAMINATION RELEASE, AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. UPON THE SHIPMENT ARRIVING AT THE TRANSFER FACILITY, THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED FROM THE ROLL-OFF TRUCK, IN PROCESS TO BE LOADED ONTO A RAILCAR, THE LOAD THE LOAD SHIFTED AGAIN TOWARD THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER FROM THE ROLL-OFF UNLOADING PROCEDURE IN WHICH A BREACHED OF THE CONTAINER OCCURRED IN THE REAR (PICTURES ATTACHMENT 2) OF THE CONTAINER, ONCE AGAIN NO PROPERTY DAMAGE, INJURIES, OR CONTAMINATION RELEASE, AS A RESULT OF THE SECOND BREACH. THE DART DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCH OF THE INCIDENT BUT NO OTHER NOTIFICATIONS WERE PERFORMED FROM DART. ON DECEMBER 5, 2003, THE OPERATING COMPANY OF THE TRANSLOAD FACILITY NOTIFIED MHF-LS THAT THEY OBSERVED CONTAINER# MHFU 002402 HAVING TWO BREACHES IN A CONTAINER.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0100 HOURS ON MONDAY, DECEMBER 1 2003, A CSX TRANSPORTATION CONDUCTOR WORKING IN HAMLET YARD REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 6960 WITH FRESH LIQUID ON SIDE OF RAIL CAR. CSX MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATION'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE TANK CAR. INVESTIGATION REVEALS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS A BLOWN RUPTURE DISC AND FRACTURED SURGE PROTECTOR. YARD MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED TO REVIEW HUMP MOVEMENT RECORDS AND REVIEW PROCEDURES WITH EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN SWITCHING OPERATIONS. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS IMMEDIATELY REPLACED, HOWEVER THE SURGE PROTECTOR WAS NOT READILY AVAILABLE. column168: ACFX78438 SHOWED EVIDENCE OV VAPOR LEAKAGE ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR, INDICATING A PROBLEM IN THE MANWAY CLOSURE AS WELL AS THE EDUCTION PIPE. THE LOCKING BAR ("ONE-ARMED BANDIT") NUT WAS LOOSE BY ABOUT 2-1/4 TURNS; THE FILL HOLE GASKET HAD SHIFTED AND ALLOWED VAPORS TO LEAK FROM THE CAR. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS INTACT.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, 2 OF 4 BOLTS ON THE EDUCTION LINE FLANGE WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, AND THERE WERE 2 BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE THAT WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE GASKET WAS ADJUSTED TO ITS PROPER POSITION, THE LOCKING BAR NUT ON THE FILL HOLE COVER WAS TIGHTENED WITH THE APPROPRIATE TOOL, AND THE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND EDUCTION PIPE WERE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR WERE CLEANED OF PRODUCT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED FOR DELIVERY AND IT WAS NOTICED THAT PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT OF CONTAINERS.

UPON UNLOADING, THE DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED SOME SEEPAGE AROUND THE BUNG ON THE 2 DRUMS.  THE SEEPAGE WAS CONTAINED ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR INSTRUCTIONS.  IT WAS RECOMMENDED THAT CHEMTREC CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND REQUEST THAT THE SHIPPER SEND OUT SOMEONE TO REPLACE THE BUNGS ON THE 2 DRUMS.  THE PRODUCT COULD THEN BE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING SIX, THIRTY-TWO OUNCE PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST THIRD MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY THIRTY-TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE CARDBOARD CARTON.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE, THIRTY-TWO OUNCE PLASTIC JUG WAS LEAKING, AND THE REMAINING FIVE PLASTIC JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH DUNNAGE TO SECURE THE CARDBOARD CARTON.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, CARDBOARD CARTON AND LEAKING THIRTY-TWO OUNCE PLASTIC JUG WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TURNING A CORNER ON SIERRA COURT IN DUBLIN, CALIFORNIA, EIGHT, TWENTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL CYLINDERS TIPPED OVER INSIDE THE TRAILER, AS A RESULT OF BEING IMPROPERLY SECURED.  THE DUBLIN FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT ONE CYLINDER WAS LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY TWENTY-FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND DISSIPATED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A CRACKED EXTERNAL PIPE ON THE NECK OF THE CYLINDER.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF OAKLAND, CALIFORNIA RESPONDED AND USED SUPPLIED AIR EQUIPMENT TO REMOVE THE DAMAGED PIPE, CAUSING THE INTERNAL VALVE TO SHUT OFF AND STOP THE RELEASE. THE CYLINDERS WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE AT THE TIGER TRUCK STOP ON I-10 AT MILE MARKER 139 IN BATON ROUGE, LA, THE DRIVER INSPECTED HIS LOAD AND FOUND THAT THE TOP TO ONE TOTE IN THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER HAD POPPED OFF.  AFTER INSPECTING HIS BILLS, HE FOUND THAT THIS TOTE CONTAINED COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID.  HE REPLACED THE LID WEARING LATEX GLOVES AND RUBBER BOOTS.  HE PLACED SPILL PADS DOWN ON THE FLOOR TO ABSORB FREE LIQUIDS AND THEN CALLED INTO THE CARRIER'S DISPATCH OFFICE TO DISCUSS.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAD PERFORMED THESE ACTIONS AND INFORMED HIS DISPATCHER.  THE DRIVER WAS ASKED WHETHER THERE WAS ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE FROM BENEATH THE TOTE OR ANY DAMAGE AND HE STATED NO.  THE TOTE WAS INTACT AND ONLY A GALLON OR TWO HAD COME DOWN THE SIDE.  SINCE HE HAD RESECURED THE LID, HE WANTED TO MOVE FROM THE REST STOP AND GO PURCHASE A WRENCH TO FURTHER TIGHTEN THE BOLT ON THE LID.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED THAT THIS WAS OK, BUT TO CALL IN IF HE WAS NOT ABLE TO DO SO OR THERE WAS ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.  HE THEN CONTINUED ON THE ROUTE AND WAS STOPPED IN PASS CHRISTIAN, MS AT DOT STOP ON I-10.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LID HAD LEAKED AGAIN.  THE INSPECTOR CALLED MSDEQ, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND EMTS.  THE MSDEQ CONTACTED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WHO DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE.  THE ER CREW ARRIVED, CLEANED THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, OFF-LOADED FREIGHT, AND FOUND THAT THE LID'S GASKET WAS TWISTED. THE CREW WAS ABLE TO RE-ALIGN THE GASKET SO IT WAS PLACED PROPERLY ALONG THE LID'S LIP AND BOLTED DOWN.  THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND ABSORBENT SHOVELED INTO DRUMS WITH PPE FROM SITE PERSONNEL.  THE DRIVER AND STATE POLICE FROM THE SCENE WERE TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL DUE TO GETTING SOME MATERIAL ON THEIR SKIN.  THERE WERE CLEANED AND DISCHARGED FROM THE HOSPITAL WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AFTER THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED, THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE MSDOT TO MOVE TO THE NEXT REST STOP FOR EIGHT HOURS TO REST BEFORE CONTINUING.  THE SHIPPER WAS INFORMED AS TO THE FAILED GASKET ON THIS CONTAINER.

THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE AIR GOING TO THE TRAILER OF THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER IN ORDER TO CHANGE THE GASKET FROM THE LEAKING FITTING. THIRD, BALL VALVE ON SAMPLE TAP LOOSE, ALTHOUGH NOT DESIGNED TO OF INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES. column168: A COMMON CARRIER WAS HIRED BY AN OUTSIDE COMPANY TO UNLOAD PRODUCT FROM OUR SATELLITE STORAGE PLANT IN HAMBURG, NJ.  THE COMMON CARRIER'S DRIVER TOLD OFFICIALS @ THE SCENE THAT HE FORGOT A PART.  HE TURNED ON ALL VALVES W/ HOSE CONNECTED AND NOTHING CAME OUT.  HE DISCONNECTED HOSE FROM TRANSPORT AND MOVED HIS TRUCK, DRAGGING THE HOSE, THE BALL VALVE OPENED, PRODUCT RELEASED.  PLACED HOSE UNDER REAR TIRE OF TRANSPORT AND RAN.  THE POLICE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE RELEASE CREATED A VAPOR CLOUD THAT GOT TO A NEIGHBORING FACTORY.  THE VAPOR WAS IGNITED IN THE FACTORY CAUSING AN EXPLOSION - NO INJURIES, NO FATALITY, NO MAJOR ROAD CLOSURES.  EVAC OF THE ONE NEIGHBORING FACTORY.

column168: ASHLAND DRIVER WAS UNLOADING VAN TRAILER AT ASHLAND DOCK.  HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO MOVE THE 15 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM USING HIS HAND TO GRAB THE HANDLE ON TOP OF DRUM.  HE LOST HIS GRIP AND THE DRUM FELL ON ITS SIDE. THIS CAUSED THE PLASTIC BUNG TO POP OUT.  APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PLASTIC BUNG OR CLOSURE HAD BEEN CROSS-THREADED & THEREFORE NOT SECURE ENOUGH TO SURVIVE THE IMPACT FALLING ON ITS SIDE.  DRIVER WAS NOT WEARING LEATHER GLOVES WHICH WOULD HAVE GIVEN HIM A BETTER GRIP ON THE HANDLE.  DRIVER TO BE GIVEN ADDITIONAL REINFORCEMENT & TRAINING TO WEAR PROPER HAND PPE & TO DOUBLE CHECK TORQUE ON DRUM CLOSURES/BUNGS.
NO REMARKS

column168: THE DRIVER IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS WHEN THE UNLOADING HOSE DEVELOPED A LEAK NEXT TO THE FEMALE CONNECTION. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS. AFTER PUTTING THE LOADING ARM IN THE DOME OPENING THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LOADING ARM WITH THE REQUIRED SAFETY CHAINS. WHEN THE DRIVER THE LOADING PUMP AND THE PRODUCT STARTED TO FLOW THROUGH THE LOADING ARM IT RAISED THE ARM UP AND OUT OF THE DOME OPENING SPILLING PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE TANK AND THE CONCRETE LOADING AREA. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON A CONCRETE SURFACE. THE SULFUR HARDEN AND WAS CHIPPED UP FROM THE LOADING AREA. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT PADS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING THREE BOTTLES WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND SPEEDY-DRY.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS PLACED INTO A SEPARATE TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TERMINALS SINK AND WASHED THE AREA THOROUGHLY.  THE FIVE UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE TRAIN WAS BROUGHT TO A STOP AND THE CONDUCTOR AND LOCAL TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR. THE CAR WAS THEN FORWARDED TO THE NEAREST YARD LOCATION IN CARTERSVILLE, GEORGIA.  THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR AND PATCHED THE WELD SEAM.  APPROXIMATELY TEN (10) POUNDS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE WAS SPREAD OVER A DISTANCE OF FIFTEEN (15) MILES.  AFTER OFF LOADING AT DESTINATION THE CAR WILL BE SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR COMPLETE INSPECTION.

THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE IN THE TERMINAL YARD, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED TOWARDS THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE AND IMPROPER LOADING.  THE RIM SEPARATED FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHEN THE LOAD SHIFTED IN TRANSIT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ROBBER BOOTS, RUBBER GLOVES, AND SPEEDY-DRY. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THREE, THIRTY GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO ONE, NINETY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE TRANSPORTATION DRIVER LEFT THE KANEB LOCATION WITH 7111 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL METERED AS NET.  THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE BURLINGTON NORTH SANTE FE LOCATION LATER IN THE DAY.  HE HOOKED UP TO THE BNSF HOSE HE KICKED UP HIS PTO, HE HAD TO GET INTO HIS UNIT CAB TO IDLE THE IGNITION UP. THE DRIVER WAS SITTING IN THE CAB WHEN A BNSF EMPLOYEE APPROACHED AND TOLD THE DRIVER THERE WAS A LEAK ON THE HOSE.  THE DRIVER GO OUT OF THE UNIT AFTER SHUTTING EVERYTHING DOWN, WENT TO THE HOSE TO FIND IT WAS LEAKING. DRIVER PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS IMMEDIATELY ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND HE AND AN EE OF BNSF SHOVELED SNOW THAT WAS EFFECTED BACK INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  BNSF DID NOT HAVE THE PROPER CLIPS ON THE CUPPLER.  DRIVER ATTACHED A TIE TO FINISH THE LOADING PROCESS.  WHEN FINISHED THE BNSF METER SHOWED HE HAD LOADED 7086 GALLONS.  BNSF HAD A COMPANY COME IN FOR THE CLEANUP.

A COMPANY SPECIALIZING IN OIL CLEANUPS WAS CALLED AND ON THE SCENE WITHIN AN HOUR. THE OIL WAS CONTAINED AND DID NOT REACH NAVIGABLE WATERS. WE WORKED WITH VA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY & DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION TO CLEAN & PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE OIL & SATURATED DIRT. NO EVACUATIONS WERE NEEDED AND NO HIGHWAYS WERE CLOSED. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT WE WILL INCREASE TRAINING ABOUT MOVEMENT OF LIQUID CARGO AND THE NEED TO REDUCE SPEED ON RAMPS. THE FREQUENCY OF THIS TRAINING WILL BE INCREASED SO THAT DRIVERS KEEP THIS DANGER IN MIND CONSTANTLY.

column168: VEHICLE #1 WAS HAULING NY TRAILER REGISTRATION AC70852.  THIS IS A TANKER HAULING APPROX. 10000 UNITS OF PROPANE.  THE VEHICLE WAS EASTBOUND ON RT 39 AND WENT OFF THE ROADWAY ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF RT. 39. THE ROADWAY, AT THE POINT THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY, CURVES TO THE LEFT.  THE VEHICLE AND TRAILER WENT ON ITS SIDE (THE PASSENGER SIDE).  THE DRIVER TRIED TO CORRECT BY TURNING TO THE LEFT.  THE TRACTOR STARTED TO THE LEFT BUT WAS TIPPING WITH THE TRAILER.  THE TRACTOR CAME DOWN ON THE ROADWAY.  THE TRAILER CAME DOWN OFF THE ROADWAY.  THE TRAILER KEPT PUSHING AND DRAGGED THE TRACTOR OFF THE ROADWAY.  BOTH UNITS SLID IN THE MUD.  THE TRACTOR PIVOTED ON THE KINGPIN AND CAME TO REST ON THE DRIVERS SIDE.  THERE WERE NO SKID MARKS OR OTHER SIGNS OF EVASIVE ACTION ON THE ROADWAY.  THERE WAS NO LEAK FROM THE TANKER WHICH WAS EVENTUALLY RIGHTED BY RUSINIAK TOWING AND WINTERS TOWING. THE TRACTOR HAD TO BE CUT IN HALF TO BE RIGHTED THUS NY STATE DOT WAS NOT ABLE TO DO A FULL INSPECTION OF THE TRACTOR.  THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN BY THE COMPANY.  THE TRAILER WAS NOT INSPECTED BY DOT AS THE BRAKES HAD TO BE RELEASED AND RE-ADJUSTED IN ORDER TO BE TAKEN FROM THE SCENE.  LT. RON KENYON WAS STILL ON THE SCENE WHEN THE VICTIM WAS EXTRICATED.  HE NOTED THAT THE VICTIM WAS NOT WEARING A SEATBELT.

column168: JACK FOREHAND THE DRIVER FOR CTL HAD COMPLETED LOADING THE CARGO TANK IN THE FAR RIGHT-HAND LOADING STATION. THE DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVE SECURED THE LOADING SPOUT. THE DRIVER SECURED THE DOME OPENING AND WAS RETURNING TO THE CAB OF HIS TRACTOR IN THE FAR RIGHT-HAND LOADING STATION WHEN THE UNIT IN THE FAR LEFT-HAND LOADING STATION STARTED TO BEGIN THE LOADING PROCESS. AS THE PUMP STARTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE LOADING SPOUT THAT JACK FOREHAND HAD SECURED. THE PRODUCT THAT WAS RELEASED FROM THE LOADING SPOUT MADE CONTACT WITH THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THE DRIVERS HARDHAT. A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED OFF THE DRIVER'S HARDHAT AND ONTO THE BACK OF HIS NECK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY GOT UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER AND RINSED OFF THE PRODUCT IN THE AFFECTED AREA. THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AT THE SCENE AND THEN TRANSPORTED TO BARTOW MEMORIAL HOSPITAL FOR PRECAUTIONARY REASON. THE DRIVER WAS SCENE AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL 2-HOUR LATER. IN THE INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER FOR CTL FAILED TO CLOSE THE CUSTOMERS VALVE COMPLETELY. THIS CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED FROM THE LOADING SPOUT WHEN THE PUMP WAS STARTED. CORRECTIVE ACTION: THE DRIVER WAS COUNSEL ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES AND CONTROLS HAVE BEEN PUT IN PLACE THAT WILL PREVENT THE DRIVER FROM ENTERING THE LOADING AREA  AND WALKING UNDER THE LOADING ARMS. THE DRIVERS WILL HAVE TO WALK AROUND THE LOADING AREA TO THE FRONT OF THEIR UNITS TO GAIN ACCESS TO THEIR UNITS. THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS RELEASED BACK TO FULL DUTY THE SAME DAY AND DID NOT LOSE ANY TIME AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. THE DRIVER AT THE TIME THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED HE WAS WEARING ALL OF THE REQUIRED PPE.

column168: ON DECEMBER 7, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:05 A.M. OUR TRANSPORT (TRACTOR 1311/TRAILER 141) WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE VEHICLE ROLLOVER THAT RESULTED IN A FATALITY AND LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 130 GALLONS OF DIESEL (UN1993) CAS-68334305) AND 5 TO 10 GALLONS OF ENGINE OIL (CAS-64742547). TROOPER KEVIN SCOTT NOTIFIED ME AT 7:00 A.M. ON DECEMBER 7, 2003 THAT WE HAD A ROLLOVER AND NEEDED INFORMATION ON THE LOAD, DRIVER, WHAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE CO. WE USED, ETC. WE OBTAINED THE NECESSARY INFORMATION, COMMUNICATED THIS INFORMATION TO TROOPER KEVIN SCOTT AND THEN NOTIFIED LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZMAT AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 A.M. AND WERE GIVEN AN INCIDENT NUMBER 03-08572. ALSO, WE NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND WERE GIVEN AN INCIDENT NUMBER 708335. THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY 4 MILE SOUTH OF ST FRANCESVILLE, LA ON U.S. HWY 61. OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON U.S. HWY 61 FROM BATON ROUGE. U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE, AS WAS ROADRUNNER TOWING AND RECOVERY, INC. DAN BEZET, HERCULES FLEET MANAGER, WAS CALLED AND ASKED TO OVERSEE THE TRANSFER OF PROPANE AND PROVIDE THE TRANSPORT AND DRIVER TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE FOR THE OFFLOADING PROCESS. ALSO, WE HAD A SECOND DRIVER BRING A TRACTOR TO THE SCENE FOR TRANSPORT OF TRAILER 141 AFTER IT HAD BEEN RECOVERED FROM THE ACCIDENT. WE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 A.M. AND FOUND THAT THE TRACTOR 1311 ONLY HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A FIRE FOLLOWING THE ROLLOVER. THE PECAN GROVE VFD HAD RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE AT APPROXIMATELY 5:33 A.M. WE DETERMINED THAT DIESEL AND ENGINE OIL HAD BEEN RELEASED AND U.S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS IN PROCESS OF RECOVERING THE REMAINING DIESEL FUEL. APPROXIMATELY 130 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS RECOVERED INTO DRUMS. REMEDIATION BY U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CONTINUES REGARDING THE ENGINE OIL AND DIESEL RELEASED TO THE DITCH BANK. ALSO, THE REMOVAL OF THE TREES AND BRUSH, AS WELL AS, MISCELLANEOUS TRUCK PARTS FROM THE AREA OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE. WE WILL AMEND THIS REPORT WHEN REMEDIATION AND REMOVAL OF MISCELLANEOUS ITEMS IS COMPLETED BY U.S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. TRAILER 141 WAS LOADED WITH 8980 GALLONS OF ODORIZED PROPANE (UN1075) (CAS68476868). TRAILER 141 WAS LOADED AT SHELL OIL CO. IN GEISMAR, LA FOR DELIVERY AT NATCHZ GAS IN NATCHEZ, MS. SHIPPING PAPERS INDICATE THAT THE LOAD WAS WEIGHED OUT AT 4:32 A.M. TRANSFER OF THE ODORIZED PROPANE BEGAN AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 A.M. FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER 141 AND WAS PAUSED FOR ABOUT 45 MINUTES DUE TO THE ARRIVAL OF A FLANGE, WHICH WAS INSTALLED, IN ORDER TO UNLOAD FROM THE SUCTION SIDE OF THE PUMP. WE BEGAN UNLOADING AT SUCTION SIDE OF PUMP AT 11:30 A.M. AT 12:45 A.M. THE SECOND TRANSFER OF ODORIZED PROPANE WAS HALTED WITH 11% REMAINING IN THE TRAILER AND THE PARTIALLY UNLOADED TRAILER WAS RECOVERED FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE. OUR SPARE TRACTOR HOOKED UP TO TRAILER 141 AND THE TRAILER WAS PULLED NORTH OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE ON U.S. HWY 61 IN ORDER TO UNLOAD THE REMAINING PR

JOHN MILLER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 11:40 PM, MGR. MILLER ADVISED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE MANWAY.  THERE WAS NO MANWAY GASKET, WHICH RESULTED IN PRODUCT SLOSHING OUT OF THE TOP. THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE RAILCAR SURFACE WITH LITTLE TO NO PRODUCT REACHING THE GROUND.  ANEW GASKET WAS APPLIED AND THE MANWAY SEALED WITH UP HAZ-MAT SEAL #0000160.  MR. MILLER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND ADVISED THEM OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE TANK CAR.

BOB TANNEHILL, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED THREE RAILCARS DERAILED IN THE PINE BLUFF YARD ON THE PINE BLUFF SUBDIVISION, MP 263 IN PINE BLUFF, AR.  MR. TANNEHILL STATED TWO OF THESE RAILCARS, TILX 620414 AND GBSR 136309, WERE DERAILED UPRIGHT AND TANKCAR UTLX 77436, CONTAINING AN ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, WAS DERAILED ON ITS SIDE WITH NO APPARENT LEAKAGE.  KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  HE DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM A BROKEN/CRACKED LIQUID VALVE. CHEMTREC, TOM FLORES, WAS NOTIFIED.

column168: TANKCAR GATX 63161 WAS REPORTEDLY RELEASING VAPORS AT UPRR ALFALFA YARD, EL PASO.  MR. JOHN JACKSON, MGR. CTS RESPONDED AND FOUND THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE LIQUID LINE VALVE PLUG "A" END WITH THE VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN. MR. JACKSON ALSO DISCOVERED THE LIQUID LINE VALVE PLUG ON THE "B" END OF THE CAR WITH THE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, BUT NOT LEAKING.  THE TANKCAR WAS SECURED, INSPECTED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION WITH NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.

ROBERT DEALBA, MANAGER OF INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED PAINT HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM OF CONTAINER UPTU 530003 WHILE PARKED AT THE INTERMODAL FACILITY THE PORT LAREDO YARD.  RAUL MEZA, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 04:28 PM, SPECIAL AGENT MEZA ADVISED THAT IT APPEARED THE TANKCAR HAD BEEN IMPACTED AND WAS CRACKED IN TWO PLACES. APPROXIMATELY TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF PAINT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  AT 06:19 PM, SPECIAL AGENT MEZA REPORTED HE WAS UNABLE TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WOULD BE DISPATCHED TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO EMPTY TANK CARS.

column168: MICHAEL GUIDRY, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED FUMES WERE DETECTED COMING FROM GATX 71658.  THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED FROM THE SOUTH END OF TRACK FOURTEEN TO THE HAZMAT TRACK 105.  THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  STATE, LOCAL, AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 08:06 PM, MANAGER ROBINSON DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM THE B END LIQUID VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  MANAGER ROBINSON REMOVED TRIAD NITROGEN SEAL #143468 AND REPLACED IT WITH UPRR HAZ/MAT SEAL #0000001 ONCE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED.  MR. ROBINSON ADVISED HE DISCUSSED THE PROBLEM AND SOLUTION WITH ALAN HAWKINS, MISSISSIPPI CHEMICALS, THE SHIPPER, TROOPER TERRY TATE OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND DANIEL LAMBERT, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY OF LOUISIANA.  LASHONDA, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY.  HAZMAT HOTLINE, WAS ALSO UPDATED.

WHILE TRANSLOADING ETHANOL FROM TANK CAR UELX 078039 TO A TANK TRUCK IN THE SPARKS YARD ON DECEMBER 4, 2003 AT 0845 HOURS, THE TANK TRUCK WAS OVERFILLED AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. THIS OCCURRED ON TRACK 769 OF THE SPARKS YARD.  THE TRANSLOADING OPERATOR STATED THAT HE HAD MADE A MISTAKE AND ENTERED 4800 GALLONS ON THE METER FOR A TRUCK THAT COULD ONLY HOLD 4200 GALLONS.  THE PUMP SHUT DOWN WHEN IT SENSED THE OVERFILL BUT BY THEN PRODUCT WAS ALREADY ON THE GROUND.  SPARKS FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  THE NEVADA EPA, WASHOE HEALTH DEPARTMENT, AND THE CITY OF SPARKS HEALTH DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED.

WHILE FILLING TANK LEG BUCKLE CAUSING OIL TO SPILL FROM TANK.  CUSTOMER TOOK RESPONSIBILITY AND CONTACTED PROFESSIONAL REMEDIATION COMPANY TO PROPERLY CLEAN, CONTAIN AND DISPOSE OF OIL SPILL.  CLEANUP IS FINISHED.

column168: (A - B) -ON 12/1/03 VESSEL GAVE NOTICE TO USCG OF ODOR COMING FROM AREA WHERE 5 CONTAINERS OF UN 3018 WAS STOWED.  HAZMAT TEAM PUT ONBOARD AT ANCHORAGE BUT NOTHING FOUND. column168: VIN BALLEJOS, CAR FOREMAN REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 46445 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CAP AND WAS LOCATED AT THE ONE SPOT IN THE COLTON YARD.  MR. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO TANK TRUCK AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: CSE EMPLOYEE F. JACKSON DISCOVERED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL WHILE UNLOADING CONWAY SOUTHERN EXPRESS TRAILER 313-9312 AT THE MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE SERVICE CENTER.  THE SHIPMENT HAD PLYWOOD DUNNAGE ON ALL SIDES OF THE SKID.  HOWEVER, A CARDBOARD CARTON BOX ON THE BOTTOM LAYER OF SKID STACKED THREE IN THREE LAYERS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. HURT PLACED THE DAMAGED BOX AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO TWO PLASTIC RECOVERY PAILS.  THE PROPER PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN ON PROTECTING THE SHIPMENT, HOWEVER, THE BOX WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.

column168: AN ASME PROPANE STORAGE TANK LOCATED BEHIND A CUSTOMER'S HOUSE WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A LEAK AT THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL OUTLET WHEN WE WERE ADDING PROPANE TO THE TANK.  THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL OUTLET PLUG WAS TIGHTENED TO PERMANENTLY STOP THE LEAK.  THE TELEPHONIC NOTICE REPORT GENERATOR (ID#782036) DESCRIPTION IS INCORRECT.  MATERIAL DID NOT SPILL OUT OF A DELIVERY TRUCK AND THE TANK WAS NOT OVERFILLED.  ABOUT 10 MINUTES PASSED FROM ADDING PROPANE TO THE TANK UNTIL THE LEAK WAS PERMANENTLY FIXED CAUSING VAPORIZATION OF ABOUT 20 GALLONS OF PROPANE.  BY THE TIME THE DRIVER FINISHED ADDING PROPANE, THE VAPOR HAD BEEN SAFELY DISBURSED.
